Subject to the second and third paragraphs, a covered motor vehicle lane that gives access to a house's parking garages shall be considered as part of the garages. Subject to the third paragraph, a covered motor vehicle lane, which provides access to a house's parking garages, shall not be considered as part of the garages or the garage floor area, where all the following conditions are met: 1° the garages are closed and insulated from the traffic lane; 2° the roof and the walls of the traffic lane are constructed of concrete;
3° the exterior walls of the track have free openings with a total surface area of at least 25% of the total surface area of the inner surface of its surrounding walls, and these openings are spread over at least 3 exterior walls in such a way as to ensure a transverse ventilation; 4° the traffic lane is used only to allow access to garages.
A covered motor vehicle lane that provides access to parking garages serving a dwelling shall not be considered as part of garages or garage flooring if the exterior walls of the track have open openings, the total surface area of which is at least 50% of the total surface area of the inner surface of its surrounding walls, and if these openings are spread over at least 3 exterior walls in such a way as to ensure cross-sectional ventilation.

The minimum glass floor area providing natural lighting of rooms in a dwelling must be: 1° 10% of the area served by the following rooms: living room, dining room, living room and sleeping space combined with another space; 2° 5% of the area served by rooms and other rooms not mentioned above; 3° 8% of the area served by a room in a room house.
No glass flooring is required for a bathroom, bathroom, kitchen, kitchen area, laundry room, games room in the basement, undeveloped basement, hall, corridor, boiler room, technical space, storage space and any other room or space similar to these. Natural second-day lighting of a room in a dwelling is permitted when the following conditions are met: 1° lit second-day floor and 1° lit second-day floor with glass flooring providing natural lighting form parts combined within the meaning of the Code;
2° the opening between the two areas is on a plane parallel to the glass surface providing natural lighting and is situated not more than 6 m from that surface; 3° the glass surface providing natural lighting is not less than 10 % of the total surface of the combined parts.

Where the borough regulations require immunization measures for a licensed construction in a flood-risk area, the following rules shall apply: 1. no part of an opening, including a window, sigh and a garage door, shall be below the low-current zone rating; 2. no component of a first-floor floor shall be below the low-current zone rating; 3. drains shall be fitted with non-return valves;
4° the structures, foundations and floor slabs below the low current zone rating level shall be designed in accordance with the requirements of Division B, Part 4, of the Code and the design calculations and details shall demonstrate the capacity of the structures to withstand this flood by incorporating calculations relating to: (a) waterproofing; (b) structural stability; (c) the required reinforcement; and (d) the strength of concrete to tension and compression.
5° in a vessel located in the low current zone, the section of the stormwater system receiving the water from a space below the low current zone rating shall be equipped with an automatic lift pump with a minimum capacity of 2.5 L/s. The drain pipe of this pump shall be connected to the stormwater system of the vessel above the low current zone rating level and shall be equipped with a return valve;
6° sections of a storm sewer connection, a main storm collector and a rain drain below the low current area's rating level must be watertight and without drainage openings. When the immunisation of a construction involves the filling of the land, it must be limited to immediate protection around the construction and not extended to the whole terrain; the average slope, from the top of the embankment adjacent to the proposed construction, to its foot, must not be less than 33 1/3 % (relative of 1 vertical and 3 horizontal).

The permit is issued to the owner if all of the following conditions are met: 1. the application complies with the zoning and construction regulations and, if applicable, with the regulations made under sections 116 and 145.21 of the Planning and Town Planning Act (R.S.Q., c. A-19.1); 2. the applicant has provided the information required to enable the competent authority to complete the form provided for in section 120.1 of the Planning and Town Planning Act (R.S.Q., c. A-19.1);
3° where the land covered by the application for a construction permit is listed on the City's list of contaminated land under section 31.68 of the Environmental Quality Act (R.S.Q., c. Q-2) and is subject to a rehabilitation plan approved by the Minister, the application shall be accompanied by an expert's certificate that the project is compatible with the provisions of the rehabilitation plan referred to above;
4° the application for a permit shall be accompanied by a written statement by the applicant that the permit applied for concerns a building intended for use as a residence for the elderly as defined in the second paragraph of section 118.1 of the Planning and Town Planning Act (R.S.Q., c. A-19.1); 5° where the application for a permit concerns a project subject to an architectural settlement and integration plan, the plans for the establishment and architecture of the building have been approved.

